SF is blessed with a bounty of high caliber bakeries and Tartine is one of the city's best. It's been about eight years since I was last here and this place is just as good as I remember. The croissants are a little more browned than other bakery's croissants. I adore the shellaced top layer that I can peel off and eat like a piece of fried chicken skin. I had some croissants from Arsicault recently and they are totally different. Arsicault's are delicate and more moist than Tartine's, but I enjoy both types and would eat either of them any day. I loved almost everything I ate. The croissant, chocolate croissant, banana cream tart, morning bun, and croque monsieur were all amazing. The pickled carrrot that came with the croque monsieur was pretty, but it was too salty to enjoy. The hazelnut chocolate tarte looked delicious, but it had more of a dry brownie texture than I thought it would (I was hoping for more of a chocolate ganache). It also had some spice in it like cinnamon or something that was off-putting for me. On a recent visit, I tried a chocolate Ã©clair and it might be my favorite version. Perfectly chilled, slightly crisp choux, tasty real vanilla in the crÃ¨me pÃ¢tissiÃ¨re, glazed with dark chocolate - a classic well done. I was a little hesitant to get it because "Wow, that's an expensive Ã©clair." The place is pretty small. Not enough tables and chairs. The line can be long at times. We waited about 30-40 mins in line before we could order. The line at the other, larger location "Tartine Manufactory" is shorter I think.

We love Tartine and would always get desserts for family get togethers. My cuz is known for standing in line or sending her kid in to get treats for holiday dinners. The desserts are not only lovely, but taste amazing. We have never had a bad item from Tartine. Tarts, pastries, cakes, it is all fantastic!.

The chocolate from the other tart kind of helped balance it out for us but individually it was a let down.

Tartine was on my list of places to try for the longest time ever, but the location and the neverending lines often discouraged me from going there. Finally, my desire to eat that delicious Devil's chocolate cake overwhelmed me and I just had to go and get in line. My friends and I went to Tartine at about 2:00 pm on a Saturday afternoon. There was a healthy line outside, but nothing too crazy. The line moved quickly and we were at the counter before we knew it. My friends got an eclair and a chocolate chip cookie while I went with the Devil's chocolate cake. After we paid, we had quite a hard time finding a place to sit as it was super packed on the inside. Fortunately for us, a large party of people sitting outside left just as we were exiting the bakery. Now flavorwise, if you love chocolate *like I do*, you will fall head over heels for the Devil's chocolate cake. It was dense, rich, and incredibly chocolatey without being overwhelmingly sweet. It was definitely on the heavier side and I had to sit around for about an hour and eat it slowly so I didn't overdose on sugar and chocolate, but I personally loved it. My friends both enjoyed their desserts and I was also able to grab a bite of both items. The cookie was delicious and the eclair filling had such a natural vanilla flavor that I kept wanting more. Overall, the desserts were all super great. The downside to this place is that it is quite popular. Lines can get crazy and there may not always be much seating. However, I highly recommend that you drop by and grab some dessert to go or plop down at a nearby park and enjoy it.

The food at Tartine did not disappoint. We ordered the kale and sun dried tomato quiche, croque monsieur, a morning bun, a croissant and the banana creme pie and they were all better than we expected. The quiche was flavorful and had a smooth consistency. The croque monsieur was made on a delicious dense and spongy bread smothered in melted cheese. The morning bun was sweet and sticky and had nice notes of orange. The croissant was flaky on the exterior and was everything you would want a good croissant to be. The banana creme pie was my favorite! It had slices of banana in a chocolate coated tart with a fresh and creamy pudding like filling. It was definitely worth every calorie! The space itself is very small and there were only a couple of tables to sit at. There is not a lot of parking available so I would recommend Uber or taking public transportation to avoid the hassle.

This review is for the Chocolate Chip Cookie. I consider myself a bit of a connoisseur - - I try pretty much every chocolate chip cookie at every bakery I see. Tartine makes, hands down, the best chocolate chip cookie in the city! It's properly crisp with complex flavors - - a veritable symphony of notes passes you by as you bite into it and chew it to completion. I double park and wait in line any time I'm nearby - - it's that good! I was going to dock the place a star for its service, but I decided that, when it comes down to it, what really matters to people is the quality of the goods and not politeness, so I decided against penalizing the establishment. That being said, the people behind the counter who, I believe, ascribe to a variety of genders (Don't get me wrong, I'm completely supportive) are kind of rude, or, at best, stuck up. Every time I gush about the cookie, they act above it all. A little appreciation would be welcome. I'm a great ambassador for their cookies!

Ok I am not a dessert person but this was AMAZING. We were on our way to Dolores Park around 6 pm when my local friend pointed out there was no line and said we had to see if there were any Banana Cream tarts left. We were in luck and let me tell you this would have been worth the wait. The crust is flaky, the banana and cream and chocolate all work so well together and there was some sort of syrup at the bottom that tasted like toffee and caramel. Such a high quality dessert! It was also very shareable and we would have taken it to the park if it had been a little warmer.

Had to try this place given the positive reviews. It totally holds up. It's a small spot that surprisingly held everyone eating, ordering and waiting in line (which wound out the door on a Monday morning). I waited for maybe 10 min - really not that bad. But it didn't have a touristy feel. Most people in line seemed to be locals. The service was quick and helpful. I had the frangipane croissant and a cafe au lait. Easily the best croissant I've ever had. Big and super filling. Incredibly flaky, but not dry. Filled with a delicious almond filling and and topped with more tasty almond slivers. The cafe au lait was so good too. No extra cream or sugar needed. Served in a big soup bowl that requires both hands to drink. Both super simple and refined yet packed with flavor. I wish I lived in the area - I would come back so many more times to try everything else that also looked amazing. This is a must in SF.

I'm okay to pay $$ for the greatest food. But, $7 for a slice of passion fruit bavarian cake is waaaaay over the top since I dont think it uses real passion fruit. But, hey, once in a lifetime kind of thing.

    1 check-in

    Had to try this place given the positive reviews. It totally holds up.

    It's a small spot that surprisingly held everyone eating, ordering and waiting in line (which wound out the door on a Monday morning). I waited for maybe 10 min - really not that bad. But it didn't have a touristy feel. Most people in line seemed to be locals. The service was quick and helpful.

    I had the frangipane croissant and a cafe au lait. Easily the best croissant I've ever had. Big and super filling. Incredibly flaky, but not dry. Filled with a delicious almond filling and and topped with more tasty almond slivers. The cafe au lait was so good too. No extra cream or sugar needed. Served in a big soup bowl that requires both hands to drink. Both super simple and refined yet packed with flavor.

    I wish I lived in the area - I would come back so many more times to try everything else that also looked amazing. This is a must in SF.
